'''Annaly Capital Management''' is one of the largest [[mortgage]] [[real estate investment trust]]s. It is organized in [[Maryland]] with its principal office in [[New York City]].<ref name=10K/>

The company borrows money, primarily via short term [[repurchase agreement]]s, and reinvests the proceeds in [[Asset-backed security|asset-backed securities]]. As of December 31, 2018, 90% of the company's assets were [[Mortgage-backed security|mortgage-backed securities]] issued by either [[Fannie Mae]] or [[Freddie Mac]]. The company generates profits from the [[net interest spread]] between the interest earned from its assets and its borrowing costs, which is amplified from the use of [[Leverage (finance)|leverage]]. As of December 31, 2018, the company had a [[debt-to-equity ratio]] of 6.3.<ref name=10K/>

As of December 31, 2017, the weighted average days to [[Maturity (finance)|maturity]] of its repurchase agreements was 77 days.<ref name=10K/>

The company is externally managed by Annaly Management Company LLC, which owned by executives of Annaly Capital Management, and pays an annual fee of 1.05% of [[Equity (finance)|equity]] for management services.<ref name=10K/>

The company is ranked 766th on the [[Fortune 500]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://fortune.com/fortune500/annaly-capital-management/ | title=Fortune 500: Annaly Capital Management}}</ref>

The name of the company came from the name of the area in [[Ireland]] that was ruled by the ancestors of the company's founder.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.fool.com/investing/dividends-income/2015/03/21/7-things-you-probably-dont-know-about-annaly-capit.aspx | title=7 Things You Probably Don't Know About Annaly Capital Management Inc. | first=Dave | last=Koppenheffer | work=[[The Motley Fool]] | date=March 21, 2015}}</ref>

==History==
Annaly Capital Management was founded in 1997 by Michael A.J. Farrell and Wellington Denahan.  Mike Farrell spent 26 years working for investment banks including [[E.F. Hutton & Co.]], [[Morgan Stanley]] and [[Merrill Lynch]].<ref name=cancer>{{cite news | url=https://in.reuters.com/article/annaly-farrell/annaly-capitals-farrell-dies-after-battle-with-cancer-idINL1E8LL7QZ20121021 | title=Annaly Capital's Farrell dies after battle with cancer | work=[[Reuters]] | date=October 21, 2012}}</ref>

In 2004, the company acquired Fixed Income Discount Advisory, an investment adviser, for $40.5 million in stock.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/01/03/business/company-news-annaly-mortgage-says-it-is-acquiring-investment-adviser.html | title=ANNALY MORTGAGE SAYS IT IS ACQUIRING INVESTMENT ADVISER | agency=[[Bloomberg News]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=January 3, 2004}}</ref>

In 2012, Michael Farrell, died after battling [[cancer]].<ref name=cancer/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nytimes/obituary.aspx?page=lifestory&pid=160607245 | title=Michael Farrell: Obituary | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=October 23, 2012}}</ref>

In October 2012, co-founder, Wellington Denahan became CEO.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.housingwire.com/articles/34531-annaly-ceo-wellington-denahan-stepping-down | title=Annaly CEO Wellington Denahan stepping down}}</ref>

In 2013, the company acquired CreXus Investment for $996 million.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20130131005465/en/Annaly-Capital-Management-Announces-Agreement-Acquire-CreXus | title=Annaly Capital Management, Inc. Announces Agreement to Acquire CreXus Investment Corp. | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=January 31, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20130523006372/en/Annaly-Completes-Acquisition-CreXus-%E2%80%93-CreXus-Renamed | title=Annaly Completes Acquisition of CreXus – CreXus to be Renamed Annaly Commercial Real Estate Group | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=May 23, 2013}}</ref>

Effective September 30, 2015, Kevin Keyes was named CEO of the company.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20150720006007/en/Annaly%E2%80%99s-Board-Names-Kevin-Keyes-CEO-Effective | title=Annaly’s Board Names Kevin Keyes CEO Effective September 30, 2015 | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=July 20, 2015}}</ref>

In 2016, the company acquired Hatteras Financial for $1.5 billion in cash and stock.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20160712005771/en/Annaly-Capital-Management-Completes-Exchange-Offer-Hatteras | title=Annaly Capital Management, Inc. Completes Exchange Offer for Hatteras Financial Corp. Common Stock | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=July 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20160411005491/en/Annaly-Capital-Management-Acquire-Hatteras-Financial-Corp. | title=Annaly Capital Management, Inc. to Acquire Hatteras Financial Corp. for $1.5 Billion | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=April 11, 2016}}</ref>

In 2017, the company sold its Pingora servicing subsidiary.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20170710006268/en/Annaly-Capital-Management-Bayview-Asset-Management-LLC | title=Annaly Capital Management, Inc. and Bayview Asset Management, LLC Announce Purchase by Bayview of Pingora Loan Servicing Platform | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=July 10, 2017}}</ref>

